Here's the registration setup:

```csharp
public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

        // HttpClient + data service — one instance for the whole app
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<HttpClient>();
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<IDataService, DataService>();

        // ViewModels — new instance per request so each navigation gets fresh state
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

        // Pages — transient so each navigation creates a clean page
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

**Why these lifetimes:**

| Registration | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `HttpClient` | **Singleton** | Reusing one instance avoids socket exhaustion. |
| `IDataService` | **Singleton** | Holds the `HttpClient`, caches, or auth tokens — shared app-wide state. |
| `MainViewModel` | **Transient** | Each navigation should get fresh state (lists, selections, errors). A singleton VM would show stale data. |
| `DetailViewModel` | **Transient** | Same — each detail screen needs its own item context. |
| `MainPage` / `DetailPage` | **Transient** | Matches the transient VM; avoids UI state leaking between navigations. |

**Key rule of thumb:** services that manage connections or shared state → **singleton**. UI-layer objects (pages, view models) that represent a screen the user navigates to → **transient** so each visit starts clean.

> If a page is expensive to create and you navigate to it frequently, you can make both the page and its VM **singleton** — but then you're responsible for resetting state on each appearance (e.g., in `OnAppearing`).
